---
description: Hygiene review — run review agents in-process via `framework audit` (requires an opted-in backend: api/paid or subagent/free). Auto-detects framework vs project target. Optional positional arg = single agent shortcut; --agent <name> (repeatable) for a subset; --snapshot (force all-snapshot) or --since <ref-or-dir> (force all-delta against ref or baseline-dir); --preserve-as <dir> [--force] to snapshot the run as a dated baseline under docs/superpowers/eval-scorecards/audit-…/.
---

The hygiene review now runs **in-process** via `uv run framework audit`.

**Basic usage:**
```bash
uv run framework audit                                # all agents, auto-detect target
uv run framework audit security                       # single-agent shortcut
uv run framework audit --agent security --agent privacy  # subset
uv run framework audit --snapshot                     # force full-snapshot mode
uv run framework audit --since <ref-or-dir>           # delta against a git ref or baseline dir
uv run framework audit --preserve-as docs/superpowers/eval-scorecards/audit-<date>-<sha>
uv run framework audit --help                         # full option reference
```

**Backend required:** `framework audit` requires an AI review backend. Configure one first:
```bash
uv run framework review-config set-backend api       # paid Anthropic API (requires ANTHROPIC_RUNTIME_API_KEY)
uv run framework review-config set-backend subagent  # free CC subscription
uv run framework review-config show                  # check current config
```

**Findings:**
```bash
cat .framework/audit/latest/audit-report.md
```

There are no prepare/Workflow/finalize steps — the audit is a single command.

## Adding (and tuning) your own reviewers — optional

You don't need this to get reviewed: the bundled agents work out of the box. But if you
want a reviewer specific to *your* codebase, drop one under `.framework/reviewers/` — no
framework changes required:

```
.framework/reviewers/<name>.md      # the reviewer's domain prompt
.framework/reviewers/<name>.toml    # block_threshold / active_when / model / trigger_globs / context
.framework/reviewers/fixtures/<name>/{good,bad}/<case>/change.patch   # calibration cases
```

A reviewer named `<name>` joins the project roster automatically (it must not reuse a
built-in agent's name). To **tune** its severity bar / scope against your own fixtures,
run the calibration pass — it emits a preview changelist and applies nothing:

```bash
uv run framework reviewer-audit --target project \
  --fixtures-root .framework/reviewers/fixtures
```

If you never create `.framework/reviewers/`, nothing changes — this is entirely opt-in.
